50|$|In {{its best}} year, 1983, more than 130,000 Metros {{were sold in}} Britian; only the Ford Escort and Sierra outsold it. This was despite {{the arrival of a}} host of new <b>superminis</b> on the British market that year - the Ford Fiesta {{received}} a major facelift, and four all-new <b>superminis</b> (the Vauxhall Nova, Fiat Uno, Nissan Micra and Peugeot 205) went on sale in Britain between April and September.|$|E
50|$|As {{small family}} cars and <b>superminis</b> grew in the 1990s to the 2000s, so did city cars. After some new <b>superminis</b> grew to be over 3900 mm long (like the Ford Fiesta, Opel Corsa, the SEAT Ibiza and the Volkswagen Polo), some {{automakers}} developed city car models more than 3650 mm long. The first of these models was the Nissan Micra (2002), which is 3720 mm long and smaller than many <b>superminis</b> of the late 1990s. Other cars are the Citroën C2, Suzuki Swift, Smart Forfour, Tata Indica, and Peugeot 1007 (the last one which can also be labelled as a mini MPV). Fiat launched their new Fiat 500 in 2007, somewhat bigger than the first 500, but still only 3546 mm long.|$|E
50|$|The K12 {{was well}} {{received}} by the motor industry and set a new standard for the <b>superminis</b> that followed it.|$|E
